.H 2 "Names for Security Objects"
.iX "pathnames" "for security objects"
Because the security namespace is rooted in the Cell Directory Service (CDS) 
namespace, security objects 
have CDS pathnames, which take the following form:
.P
\*V/.../\*O\*Ecellname\*O\*L/\*O\*Emount_point\*O/\*Eobject_name\*O
.P
where:
.VL 1.25i
.LI "\*Ecellname\*O "
Is the name of the cell in which the object
resides.
.LI "\*Emount_point\*O"
Is the name under which
the DCE Security Service is registered in CDS.
.LI "\*Eobject_name\*O"
Is the name of the registry object assigned when the object is created.  
If the object resides in a directory, \*Eobject_name\*O consists of the names of
the object itself and any directories that must be traversed to access 
the object.  Note that registry objects generally reside 
in the principal, group, or organization directory in the 
registry database.  See Chapter 41 for 
a more complete description of the registry database structure.
.LE
.iX "pathnames" "for registry objects"
.iX "registry" "objects" "pathnames"
.P
For example, the full pathname for the principal \*Lbach\*O, which
resides in the cell \*Ldresden.com\*O, uses the \*Lsec\*O
(security) mount point and is in the \*Lprincipal\*O directory as follows:
.P
\*L/.../dresden.com/sec/principal/bach\*O
.P
As another example, assume the group \*Least-west\*O resides in \*Lsales\*O, 
which is a subdirectory of the \*Lgroup\*O directory in the registry
database in the \*Ldresden.com\*O cell.  The full pathname for \*Least-west \*Ois 
as follows:
.P
\*L/.../dresden.com/sec/group/sales/east-west\*O
