.zZ "def, 13575,R1.2.2,Removed acl_edit & rgy_edit index entry"
.P
.H 3 "Using Names with dcecp Security Commands"
.iX "principals" "logical identity"
.P
For all the \*Ldcecp\*O 
commands that are used to manage the DCE Security Service, except
\*Ldcecp acl\*O, you supply only an object name to identify the object you
want to manipulate.  The object names are stored in 
the registry database.  You are not required to enter a cell name (the local 
cell is assumed) or mount point (the name registered for the DCE
Security Service is assumed).
.P
.H 3 "Using Names with the dcecp acl Command"
.P
Unlike other \*Ldcecp\*O security commands, the \*Ldcecp acl\*O command 
works with ACLs that can be maintained by DCE services other
than security.  Like any generic tool that operates on
objects that can exist in different namespaces, \*Ldcecp acl\*O
requires the object's fully qualified CDS pathname  
instead of just \*Eobject_name\*O.
.P
For example, 
to use the \*Ldcecp acl\*O command to change the ACL that is associated
with principal \*Lbach\*O's registry account,
you must enter the following fully qualified name:
.iS
/.../dresden.com/sec/principal/bach\*O
.iE
or
.iS
/.:/sec/principal/bach\*O
.iE
Note also that, to use \*Ldcecp acl\*O to manipulate the ACL that is on the
principal directory of the registry database, and thus control
who can add or delete principals, you must enter the following fully 
qualified name:
.iS                                                            
/.../dresden.com/sec/principal\*O
.iE 
.P
In a hierarchical cell, one name can represent a directory and a principal.  
For example assume that a principal name is stored in Cell A's registry to 
represent a cell with which Cell A engages in cross-cell authentication.  
The name for the cell in the registry is
.iS
/.:/sec/principal/vienna.com\*O
.iE
.P
This cell name can also represent the name of a directory, such as
.iS
/.:/sec/principal/vienna.com/violinists_cell\*O
.iE
.P
For these cases, the \*Ldcecp acl\*O command provides an option that identifies 
whether you are entering a directory name or a principal name.
